The purpose is official tool qualification. These vendor sources establish that the tool exists as a public vendor-backed surface in this domain; they are not the external facet evidence about workflow, pricing, operations, or posture.

A valid `tool` is a named standalone product or clearly dedicated tool surface in this task's domain. Generic broad-suite modules, utility cards, menu items, adjacent writing/SEO utilities, translators, summarizers, citation/reference generators, title or meta-description generators, punctuation/spell checkers, and similar surfaces are invalid unless the vendor source ties that specific surface to AI humanization, rewriting, paraphrasing, detector/originality, or writing refinement in a non-incidental way. Multiple tools from the same vendor can count only when each tool has its own dedicated product/tool page, official app/listing, or clearly labeled page section that identifies that specific tool surface.

Requirements:
- The page should communicate a vendor-owned, vendor-controlled, or vendor-maintained source connection for the named tool, such as a vendor domain, official docs/help center, official product/tool page, pricing page, terms/privacy/ethics/disclaimer page, vendor-maintained blog/docs page, changelog, or release note. Third-party app/plugin marketplaces, app stores, software directories, review platforms, and independent articles are not vendor qualification sources merely because the vendor supplied listing copy or is mentioned there.
- The page must clearly identify the named tool or identify the vendor/product relationship that makes the named tool unambiguous. Suite-wide language such as "all tools included," "apps," "browser extensions," "AI writing tools," "API for teams," generic detector/plagiarism bundles, generic plan names, broad API availability, or a many-tool menu does not identify every module or every listed product.
- The page must tie the named tool to this task's domain through concrete AI humanizer, rewrite, paraphrase, detector/originality, AI-authorship, or writing-refinement language. Generic writing, SEO, grammar, summarization, translation, citation, or productivity language without that domain tie is not enough.
